{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Hermitian fermion bilinears always appear in two forms: with two third-generation fermions, and with two light-generation fermions.",
    "For instance, the operator Q He gives rise to the following two U(2) 5 -invariant operators:Q [33] He = (H † iD µ H)(ē 3 γ µ e 3), Q [ii] He = (H † iD µ H) i=1,2 (ē i γ µ e i).",
    "Hermitian four-fermion operators involving two different fermion species appear in four distinct forms.",
    "As an example, the operator Q ℓq gives rise to:Q (1)[3333] ℓq = ( l3 γ µ ℓ 3)(q 3 γ µ q 3), Q (1)[iijj] ℓq = i=1,2 ( li γ µ ℓ i) j=1,2 (q j γ µ q j), Q (1)[33ii] ℓq = ( l3 γ µ ℓ 3) i=1,2 (q i γ µ q i), Q (1)[ii33] ℓq = i=1,2 ( li γ µ ℓ i)(q 3 γ µ q 3).",
    "(2.3)v. Hermitian four-fermion operators involving a single fermion species (hence four identical fields but for the flavor index) can appear in up to five different configurations."
  ],
